1
00:00:04,880 --> 00:00:06,200
Stanford University.

2
00:00:08,660 --> 00:00:12,400
We do know a highly

3
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:16,140
accurate description of elementary particles.

4
00:00:20,040 --> 00:00:21,780
It has a lot of parameters.

5
00:00:23,009 --> 00:00:25,220
Depending on the particular version of it,

6
00:00:25,220 --> 00:00:26,500
which turns out to be true,

7
00:00:26,500 --> 00:00:30,820
it could vary anywhere from 25 parameters to 150.

8
00:00:32,840 --> 00:00:34,660
But of order,

9
00:00:34,660 --> 00:00:37,320
somewhere like 50,

10
00:00:37,320 --> 00:00:37,760
75,

11
00:00:37,760 --> 00:00:39,320
100 parameters,

12
00:00:39,320 --> 00:00:39,940
numbers.

13
00:00:40,200 --> 00:00:40,980
What kind of numbers?

14
00:00:41,720 --> 00:00:43,880
The masses of quarks,

15
00:00:43,880 --> 00:00:45,140
the masses of electrons,

16
00:00:45,140 --> 00:00:46,700
the masses of muons,

17
00:00:48,180 --> 00:00:49,800
the coupling constants,

18
00:00:49,800 --> 00:00:53,880
the value of the electric charge of particles,

19
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:56,360
all kinds of things.

20
00:00:56,360 --> 00:00:56,940
Things like that.

21
00:00:57,460 --> 00:00:58,660
And in addition,

22
00:00:58,660 --> 00:01:01,860
just a list of what the particles are.

23
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:06,760
Some of the particles are related to

24
00:01:06,760 --> 00:01:09,600
each other in various kinds of mathematical ways.

25
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:13,300
Others of them are not

26
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:15,360
particularly simply related to each other.

27
00:01:16,060 --> 00:01:21,090
And so there's a very accurate theory that

28
00:01:21,090 --> 00:01:26,120
describes everything basically that's known about elementary particles.

29
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:28,320
Thousands of experiments.

30
00:01:29,020 --> 00:01:30,160
In principle,

31
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:32,040
it can explain nuclei.

32
00:01:32,540 --> 00:01:34,560
It can certainly explain atoms.

33
00:01:34,820 --> 00:01:36,760
Quantum electrodynamics is part of it.

34
00:01:38,100 --> 00:01:38,740
And therefore,

35
00:01:38,740 --> 00:01:41,420
it can explain molecules and chemistry.

36
00:01:42,100 --> 00:01:42,580
Of course,

37
00:01:42,580 --> 00:01:43,980
when I say it can explain it,

38
00:01:43,980 --> 00:01:47,940
I mean to say if you had infinite computing power,

39
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:52,750
that you could solve its equations

40
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:56,340
and do it with reasonably high power.

41
00:01:56,340 --> 00:01:56,680
And by precision,

42
00:01:56,680 --> 00:01:58,560
you could explain chemistry,

43
00:01:58,560 --> 00:02:00,220
molecules.

44
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:04,300
I'm not going to tell you you could explain life.

45
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:05,930
That I think I would

46
00:02:05,930 --> 00:02:07,380
get all sorts of reactions to.

47
00:02:07,720 --> 00:02:09,000
That's a separate issue.

48
00:02:10,300 --> 00:02:11,520
Consciousness and so forth.

49
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:12,780
Leave that off the table.

50
00:02:16,020 --> 00:02:17,140
Then in addition,

51
00:02:17,140 --> 00:02:18,820
we have a theory of gravity.

52
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:19,800
Oh,

53
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:20,160
of course,

54
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:24,160
the theory of fundamental particles is quantum mechanical,

55
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:25,600
heavily quantum mechanical.

56
00:02:26,420 --> 00:02:30,900
We also have a classical theory of gravity.

57
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:32,560
Einstein's field equations,

58
00:02:32,560 --> 00:02:34,180
general relativity.

59
00:02:35,060 --> 00:02:35,840
Again,

60
00:02:35,840 --> 00:02:39,440
it's a highly accurate theory.

61
00:02:41,140 --> 00:02:43,480
Does it have any parameters in it?

62
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:44,560
Well,

63
00:02:44,560 --> 00:02:46,000
it has Newton's constant.

64
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:52,030
It's worthwhile spending a few minutes asking

65
00:02:52,030 --> 00:02:55,020
what the fundamental quantities are in physics.

66
00:02:58,140 --> 00:03:00,680
There's all sorts of quantities

67
00:03:00,680 --> 00:03:03,220
like the mass of the proton,

68
00:03:03,580 --> 00:03:06,900
or more exactly,

69
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:10,100
the ratios of masses of particles.

70
00:03:10,840 --> 00:03:12,270
Ratio of the mass of the

71
00:03:12,270 --> 00:03:13,700
proton to the mass of the electron.

72
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:15,680
All those are parameters.

73
00:03:16,100 --> 00:03:18,400
They're not thought to be highly,

74
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:19,120
deeply,

75
00:03:19,120 --> 00:03:19,960
deeply fundamental.

76
00:03:21,240 --> 00:03:23,340
They're not universal parameters.

77
00:03:24,219 --> 00:03:27,509
They're specific parameters that have to do with

78
00:03:27,509 --> 00:03:30,800
the proton and the electron in this case.

79
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,060
If I was to substitute for

80
00:03:33,060 --> 00:03:35,120
the proton some other similar particle,

81
00:03:35,120 --> 00:03:36,360
the neutron for example,

82
00:03:36,540 --> 00:03:39,900
and substitute for the electron the mu particle,

83
00:03:39,900 --> 00:03:41,660
which is very similar to the electron,

84
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:44,000
would be an entirely different ratio.

85
00:03:45,700 --> 00:03:47,120
Where they came from,

86
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:48,180
why they're there,

87
00:03:48,180 --> 00:03:49,220
what they reflect,

88
00:03:49,220 --> 00:03:50,220
we don't really know.

89
00:03:50,520 --> 00:03:52,580
But they don't seem to have any,

90
00:03:52,580 --> 00:03:53,180
you know,

91
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:55,240
really broad generality.

92
00:03:56,440 --> 00:03:58,140
There are a couple of parameters,

93
00:03:58,140 --> 00:04:00,260
three of them to be precise,

94
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:02,460
which have great generality.

95
00:04:02,540 --> 00:04:05,160
And I'll explain what I mean by generality and universality.

96
00:04:06,040 --> 00:04:07,540
First of all is the speed of light.

97
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:11,240
In what sense is the speed of light universal?

98
00:04:11,580 --> 00:04:11,700
Well,

99
00:04:11,700 --> 00:04:14,260
when you think about what Einstein's principle says,

100
00:04:14,520 --> 00:04:18,360
it says that all matter and all information

101
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:22,200
moves with less than the speed of light.

102
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:24,140
The key word there is all.

103
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:27,240
Whenever you have one of these statements that all such

104
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:29,520
and such and such and such and such and such,

105
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:30,980
some law of physics,

106
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:33,080
when that word all is there,

107
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:35,490
you know that it has to do

108
00:04:35,490 --> 00:04:37,900
with something deep and fundamental and universal.

109
00:04:38,380 --> 00:04:38,860
So,

110
00:04:38,860 --> 00:04:40,000
there's the speed of light.

111
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:42,080
See.

112
00:04:44,140 --> 00:04:44,620
Next,

113
00:04:44,620 --> 00:04:45,480
Planck's constant.

114
00:04:46,980 --> 00:04:50,220
Is Planck's constant just some random number

115
00:04:50,220 --> 00:04:53,160
that has only to do with one specific number?

116
00:04:53,180 --> 00:04:54,140
Is it a specific kind of phenomenon?

117
00:04:54,880 --> 00:04:55,780
Or is it,

118
00:04:55,780 --> 00:04:57,440
again,

119
00:04:57,440 --> 00:04:58,900
a universal quantity?

120
00:04:59,440 --> 00:05:00,020
Well,

121
00:05:00,020 --> 00:05:01,400
in this case,

122
00:05:01,400 --> 00:05:02,660
it's the uncertainty principle.

123
00:05:03,020 --> 00:05:06,420
The uncertainty principle says for all particles,

124
00:05:06,620 --> 00:05:07,560
and not only particles,

125
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:08,860
for all objects,

126
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:09,520
period,

127
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:12,240
the uncertainty in the position

128
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:14,560
times the uncertainty in the momentum

129
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:17,540
is always greater than or equal to h-bar.

130
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:17,940
Again,

131
00:05:17,940 --> 00:05:21,320
the word all comes up repeatedly in that sentence.

132
00:05:21,320 --> 00:05:22,960
And so,

133
00:05:22,960 --> 00:05:23,740
h-bar,

134
00:05:23,740 --> 00:05:24,680
Planck's constant,

135
00:05:25,560 --> 00:05:29,920
is also a very fundamental constant.

136
00:05:31,460 --> 00:05:34,260
And fundamental in the sense of universal.

137
00:05:34,760 --> 00:05:36,400
Governs all phenomena,

138
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:39,340
not just some specific particular kind of particle,

139
00:05:39,500 --> 00:05:40,580
but all particles,

140
00:05:40,580 --> 00:05:42,600
all objects,

141
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:43,080
period.

142
00:05:43,740 --> 00:05:45,300
And finally,

143
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:46,580
there's Newton's constant.

144
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:49,520
Remember Newton's law of gravity?

145
00:05:49,520 --> 00:05:56,180
All objects attract each other with a force

146
00:05:56,180 --> 00:05:59,060
that is inverse to the distance between them,

147
00:05:59,120 --> 00:06:01,240
inverse squared to the distance between them,

148
00:06:01,380 --> 00:06:04,180
and proportional to the product of the masses

149
00:06:04,180 --> 00:06:07,340
times a constant called Newton's constant,

150
00:06:07,340 --> 00:06:08,320
capital G,

151
00:06:11,240 --> 00:06:15,040
that is the same for all possible objects.

152
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:19,500
When a little bit of relativity is added in,

153
00:06:19,520 --> 00:06:21,500
mass becomes energy,

154
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:24,760
and so all forms of energy attract each other,

155
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:29,040
but the universal constant G is always there.

156
00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:35,400
So this use of the word all in the laws

157
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:39,580
for which these things are the numbers associated with them

158
00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:43,220
is apparently deep.

159
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:47,880
Planck was really the first one to realize this.

160
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:50,600
He was the first one to realize how fundamental...

161
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:51,440
Now at that time,

162
00:06:51,440 --> 00:06:54,420
he didn't even know what h-bar really meant.

163
00:06:55,100 --> 00:06:57,320
He had parameterized radiation,

164
00:06:57,320 --> 00:06:59,540
thermal radiation,

165
00:06:59,840 --> 00:07:00,840
black body radiation,

166
00:07:00,840 --> 00:07:02,760
by this quantity h-bar.

167
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:04,520
He didn't really know what it meant.

168
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:07,440
He didn't know what quantum mechanics was going to be,

169
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:08,570
that it was going to be a

170
00:07:08,570 --> 00:07:09,680
whole new way of thinking about things.

171
00:07:10,440 --> 00:07:12,820
He just had discovered this new constant,

172
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,080
which together with C and

173
00:07:15,080 --> 00:07:17,160
G gave three constants of nature.

174
00:07:18,159 --> 00:07:19,420
And ultimately,

175
00:07:19,420 --> 00:07:19,960
of course,

176
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:21,000
we did find out

177
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:22,600
that these three constants are

178
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:24,200
deep and fundamental and universal,

179
00:07:24,560 --> 00:07:26,960
but Planck sort of suspected it.

180
00:07:27,300 --> 00:07:29,460
And the other thing he realized,

181
00:07:29,460 --> 00:07:31,420
which is also very important,

182
00:07:31,660 --> 00:07:36,880
is that there are three units of...

183
00:07:36,880 --> 00:07:39,180
three dimensional units in physics,

184
00:07:39,460 --> 00:07:42,160
which are the three basic

185
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:44,860
dimensional units that we work with.

186
00:07:45,060 --> 00:07:46,400
One of them is length,

187
00:07:48,060 --> 00:07:49,820
one of them is time,

188
00:07:49,940 --> 00:07:50,840
units of length,

189
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:51,740
units of time,

190
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:53,640
and units of mass.

191
00:07:56,260 --> 00:07:57,820
What he also realized

192
00:07:59,100 --> 00:08:02,500
is that the units of C,

193
00:08:02,500 --> 00:08:03,440
h-bar,

194
00:08:03,440 --> 00:08:03,940
and G

195
00:08:03,940 --> 00:08:06,820
were such that you could combine them

196
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:09,700
and make units of length,

197
00:08:09,700 --> 00:08:10,160
time,

198
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:10,840
and mass.

199
00:08:12,240 --> 00:08:15,240
So that means that there's some fundamental...

200
00:08:15,240 --> 00:08:16,780
there are fundamental constants here,

201
00:08:16,780 --> 00:08:17,380
and these constants,

202
00:08:17,380 --> 00:08:18,120
incidentally,

203
00:08:18,120 --> 00:08:19,320
carry dimensions.

204
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,420
They're not dimensionless.

205
00:08:21,620 --> 00:08:23,360
They're not like ratios of masses,

206
00:08:23,360 --> 00:08:24,400
which are dimensionless.

207
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:25,220
They carry dimensions.

208
00:08:26,620 --> 00:08:28,220
The units of length,

209
00:08:28,220 --> 00:08:28,640
time,

210
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:30,220
and mass also carry dimensions.

211
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:33,380
And what it meant is you could make up...

212
00:08:33,380 --> 00:08:34,100
not make up,

213
00:08:34,100 --> 00:08:37,240
you could derive a basic unit of length,

214
00:08:37,539 --> 00:08:39,340
a basic unit of time,

215
00:08:39,520 --> 00:08:41,840
and a basic unit of mass

216
00:08:42,690 --> 00:08:43,980
from these three quantities.

217
00:08:46,780 --> 00:08:47,200
So we do it?

218
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:48,560
Okay.

219
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:51,260
It's called dimensional analysis.

220
00:08:51,660 --> 00:08:53,560
The first thing we have to find out is

221
00:08:53,560 --> 00:08:55,800
what is the units of C,

222
00:08:55,800 --> 00:08:57,240
h-bar,

223
00:08:57,240 --> 00:08:57,740
and G?

224
00:08:57,880 --> 00:08:59,700
Here's the way you do dimensional analysis.

225
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:02,140
You first make sure you know what the dimensions

226
00:09:02,140 --> 00:09:04,980
of the quantities that you're dealing with are.

227
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:07,760
And the symbol for the dimension of a quantity

228
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:09,680
is just a square bracket like this.

229
00:09:10,200 --> 00:09:11,960
This doesn't stand for the speed of light.

230
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,020
It stands for the dimensions of the speed of light.

231
00:09:14,100 --> 00:09:14,320
All right,

232
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:16,760
what's the dimensions of a velocity?

233
00:09:17,420 --> 00:09:18,440
Length over time.

234
00:09:18,640 --> 00:09:19,620
Length over time.

235
00:09:19,820 --> 00:09:20,960
So that's length over time.

236
00:09:23,620 --> 00:09:24,320
All right,

237
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:28,540
what's the dimension of Planck's constant?

238
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:30,600
The dimension of Planck's constant,

239
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:31,400
h-bar?

240
00:09:32,340 --> 00:09:33,140
One over what?

241
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:34,800
One over L squared over two.

242
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:36,560
Probably right,

243
00:09:36,560 --> 00:09:37,880
but I have to do it.

244
00:09:38,820 --> 00:09:40,200
Let's see if we can figure it out.

245
00:09:41,220 --> 00:09:44,520
We need an equation that involves h-bar.

246
00:09:44,720 --> 00:09:46,760
The basic equation that involves h-bar

247
00:09:46,780 --> 00:09:49,380
always involves distance times momentum,

248
00:09:49,380 --> 00:09:49,860
right?

249
00:09:50,080 --> 00:09:50,940
Uncertainty principle.

250
00:09:51,620 --> 00:09:52,740
Distance times momentum.

251
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:54,340
All right,

252
00:09:54,340 --> 00:09:55,640
so the units of h-bar

253
00:09:55,640 --> 00:09:58,180
are the units of length times momentum,

254
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:01,180
but momentum is mass times velocity.

255
00:10:01,960 --> 00:10:05,060
So it's mass times velocity,

256
00:10:05,220 --> 00:10:07,160
and a velocity is another L over T,

257
00:10:07,320 --> 00:10:09,160
so that's L squared over T,

258
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:10,720
and I think somebody said that.

259
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:12,120
Length squared,

260
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:13,260
mass over time.

261
00:10:13,340 --> 00:10:14,680
I don't know how you knew that so fast.

262
00:10:14,820 --> 00:10:15,880
How did you know that so fast?

263
00:10:16,900 --> 00:10:17,640
Memorize it?

264
00:10:17,720 --> 00:10:18,180
Who did it?

265
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:20,520
Some guy back there,

266
00:10:20,520 --> 00:10:20,780
okay.

267
00:10:22,620 --> 00:10:23,460
Mass squared,

268
00:10:23,460 --> 00:10:23,860
okay,

269
00:10:23,860 --> 00:10:24,780
there we go.

270
00:10:25,100 --> 00:10:26,140
And finally,

271
00:10:26,140 --> 00:10:27,300
Newton's constant.

272
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:27,720
All right,

273
00:10:27,720 --> 00:10:30,900
we need a formula that involves Newton's constant.

274
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:34,760
Why not take the basic formula that Newton started with?

275
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:43,800
Force is equal to mass times mass times g

276
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:47,640
divided by distance squared,

277
00:10:47,640 --> 00:10:48,100
right?

278
00:10:48,200 --> 00:10:48,800
R squared.

279
00:10:50,120 --> 00:10:50,620
Okay,

280
00:10:50,620 --> 00:10:51,020
well,

281
00:10:51,020 --> 00:10:52,260
we're not quite finished

282
00:10:52,260 --> 00:10:55,000
because we have to know the units of force.

283
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:56,900
Now,

284
00:10:56,900 --> 00:10:58,380
we're trying to find the units of g.

285
00:10:58,820 --> 00:11:00,260
What are the units of force?

286
00:11:00,620 --> 00:11:01,080
Well,

287
00:11:01,080 --> 00:11:02,880
we use another Newton equation.

288
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:04,320
Mass times acceleration.

289
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:08,320
Mass times acceleration.

290
00:11:08,500 --> 00:11:09,480
We can cancel.

291
00:11:09,680 --> 00:11:11,500
We're only interested in the units now.

